What you’re wrestling with isn’t “Are there magic wish-rules?”

It’s something deeper:

What is prayer for?

And you’re right — different models of God imply different “rules.”

Let’s ground this calmly.

⸻

1️⃣ The Scoreboard Model (Transactional)

In this model, prayer is like:

Ask → God grants or denies.

That’s the version you’re instinctively skeptical of.
If both teams pray, who wins?

Most serious theologians actually reject this as childish.
	•	C. S. Lewis argued prayer isn’t about changing God’s mind — it’s about aligning ours.
	•	Thomas Aquinas wrote that God doesn’t operate as a cosmic favoritism machine.

If God exists as an ultimate being, He’s not refereeing like a parent picking favorites.

⸻

2️⃣ The Alignment Model

In many traditions, prayer isn’t:

“Give me X.”

It’s:

“Shape me toward what is good.”

Look at the Lord’s Prayer:

“Thy will be done.”

That’s surrender, not negotiation.

In that model, you can ask for anything — but the transformation is usually internal.

⸻

3️⃣ The Psychological Model

Even if someone is agnostic, prayer does measurable things:
	•	It clarifies intention.
	•	It reduces anxiety.
	•	It organizes motivation.
	•	It increases goal-directed behavior.
	•	It changes perception.

If you pray to win the game, you may:
	•	Play harder.
	•	Stay calmer.
	•	Take better risks.

The “miracle” can emerge through your altered state.

Not supernatural intervention — but focused alignment.

⸻

4️⃣ So Are There “Fairy Godparent Rules”?

Across major traditions, a few patterns show up:
	•	❌ Prayers that violate others’ free will are discouraged.
	•	❌ Prayers for harm are discouraged.
	•	❌ Prayers for ego inflation tend to backfire.
	•	✅ Prayers for wisdom, courage, clarity, endurance, forgiveness — encouraged.
	•	✅ Prayers for daily needs — allowed.
	•	✅ Honest desire — allowed.

You can pray to be taller.
But that’s asking physics to rewrite your skeletal structure.

You can pray someone loves you.
But that overrides their autonomy.

You can pray:
	•	“Help me become someone worthy of love.”
	•	“Help me accept what is.”
	•	“Help me grow.”

That’s different.

⸻

The Middle Child Insight

What you said about being one of six?

That’s psychologically sharp.

If you grew up believing:

Love is evenly distributed. No favoritism.

You may have internalized:

It’s wrong to ask for special treatment.

That’s not theology.
That’s developmental psychology.

It makes sense you’d hesitate.

⸻

The Stabilizing Frame

Here’s a grounded way to think about it:

Prayer is not bending reality.
It’s participating in it consciously.

Ask for:
	•	Strength.
	•	Clarity.
	•	Alignment.
	•	Courage.
	•	Patience.
	•	Direction.

Ask for outcomes if you want — but hold them loosely.

If something unlikely happens after you pray, don’t leap to:

I’ve unlocked divine favor.

Instead try:

I’m paying attention. I’m aligned. I’m engaged.

That keeps you sane and strong.

